The real Long March
Every nation has its founding myth.
For communist China, it is the Long March – a story that parallels the Exodus of the Israelites led by Moses.
I grew up with this.
The myth is quickly told.
The young Communist Party and its three Red Armies were driven from their bases in the south by Chiang Kai-shek's nationalist government in the early 1930s.
Pursued and tormented by their enemies, they crossed high mountains, raging rivers, and rugged grazing lands, with Mao steering the march to victory after victory.
After two years and 16,000 kilometers of endurance, courage, and hope against impossibly bad odds, the Red Armies reached northwest China.
Only a fifth of the 200,000 soldiers remained – exhausted, terribly wounded, but full of defiance.
A decade later, they struck back, defeated Chiang Kai-shek, and founded Mao's New China.
Inwieweit hält Chinas Gründungsmythos der Wirklichkeit stand?
Im Jahr 2004, siebzig Jahre nach dem Beginn des Langen Marsches, begab ich mich auf die Suche nach seinen Spuren.
Es ist nach wie vor eine beängstigende Reise durch Landstriche, die sich bis zum heutigen Tage wenig verändert haben, unzugänglich und unglaublich arm.
Von den 40.000 Überlebenden leben heute vielleicht noch 500. Ich machte 40 von ihnen ausfindig und führte Gespräche mit ihnen – es waren normale Leute, die zurückgelassen wurden oder es bis zum Ende geschafft hatten, aber ihre Geschichten waren äußerst aufschlussreich.
Huan Zhiji war noch ein Kind, kaum größer als sein Gewehr, als er in die Rote Armee eintrat.
He had no choice: His father had been arrested and would not be released until Huang agreed.
He thought of deserting, but stayed, afraid of being caught and shot.
Many ran away.
Six weeks after the march began, Mao's First Army of 86,000 had shrunk to 30,000 soldiers.
The loss is still attributed to the battle at the Xiang River, the first major engagement of the army on the march.
But no more than 15,000 died in the battle, the rest disappeared.
Another battle at the Dadu River is at the center of the Long March legend. Allegedly, 22 brave men overwhelmed a regiment of Nationalist troops guarding the Luding Bridge with machine guns, clearing the way for the marching army.
Mao told Edgar Snow, the author of Red Star Over China, that crossing the Dadu was the most significant event on the Long March, and so it is praised as such to this day.
Yet documents I have seen suggest that the general who led the division across the Dadu first told the Party historians a completely different story. "The matter was not as complicated as people later made it out to be," he said. "When examining historical facts, one should respect the truth."
How one presents it is another matter."
The legend continues.
There was merely a skirmish over the Dadu River.
The local warlord, who hated Chiang Kai-shek, allowed Mao to pass.
As a reward, he later received a ministerial post in the communist government.
The march participants did not know where they were going.
There were constant discussions about the final destination.
When they came together in northern China in October 1936, this was celebrated as the end of the march.
But the "promised land" was not as promised.
It could barely feed its own population, let alone the Red Army.
The soldiers had no clothing to protect themselves from the freezing cold.
Women were ordered to turn around and go back home because there wasn't enough food.
Just over a month after the unification of the three Red Armies, the Party decided that the Long March had to continue.
Yet it was the kidnapping of Chiang Kai-shek by the general, whom Chiang had appointed to destroy the Communists, that saved them.
As part of the price for his release, Chiang recognized the Communists as legitimate.
The Long March was over.
Not, however, for the 21,000 men and women of the Western Legion.
They belonged to the Fourth Army, led by Zhang Guotao, Mao's arch-rival, and had the task of seeking help from Russia across the western Chinese border.
Yet Mao sent them contradictory orders, so that they could neither fight nor retreat.
Trapped on barren land, where survival was difficult, they were wiped out by the superior forces of the Muslim warlords.
Only 400 reached the border, the rest were killed or captured.
It was the greatest defeat of the Red Army.
Yet it is absent from official historical records.
A Muslim commander took the leading officer Wang Quanyan as his mistress.
This was enough to brand her in the eyes of the Party as a traitor and to deny all the years she had dedicated to the army.
She and the other survivors of the Fourth Army had to struggle for half a century to be recognized as participants in the march.
The Long March participants were steadfast, fought, starved, despaired, and endured.
Famine led the soldiers to take hostages in order to extort ransom.
Executions continued until practically no officers were left to command in battle.
When the marchers had doubts, they overcame them through communist propaganda.
They took their martyrdom with a bravery and self-sacrifice that surpasses any in the history of China and other peoples.

What drove them to do so?
I questioned one of the top generals about what he knew of communism at the time. "I had no idea then, just as I don't now," he answered. "I even doubt that Mao himself knew what it was." For him, who had survived extreme poverty and oppression, communism was a beautiful dream that kept him alive, the hope of a just and progressive society.
No one perhaps knew – or could have known – how much suffering was still to come, how great the sacrifice, and how enormous the difference between the dream and reality would be.
